<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06079202 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06079202 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  AUTO; RACING; RESULT; GEORGIA  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Ken Schrader wasn't sure he could outrun Bill Elliott, but he knew he couldoutlast him.;    Schrader topped off his gas tank with 65 laps -- 97 miles --to go, and with Elliott closing fast, he won a rain-delayed $655,000 NASCARCup race Monday in Hampton, Ga.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GAS TROUBLE SLOWS ELLIOTT; SCHRADER WINSRACE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Sports Digest  </MEMO><TEXT>     Twice Elliott had to coast into his pit for fuel.;    Schrader, whofinished second at Charlotte, N.C., in the last NASCAR Cup race, won $69,250.He averaged 140.470 mph on the 1.5-mile Atlanta Motor Speedway oval.;    DaleEarnhardt finished third.;  COLLEGE FOOTBALL: Texas defensive tackle JamesPatton switched urine samples with a teammate to avoid detection of steroidsduring a drug test last August, another player told the AustinAmerican-Statesman. A former player said, &quot;It's not hard to switch. They justgive you a cup and tell you to come back.&quot;;  COLLEGES: San Jose State golferPat Hurst and sophomore teammate Tracy Hanson are ranked 1-2 in the nation bythe NCAA. The Spartans women's team is ranked No. 1, Stanford sixth. . . . TheCal-San Jose State baseball game scheduled for today was postponed until April20.;  SWIMMING: Two former Washington High (Fremont) athletes scored victoriesin the NCAA Division II championships last weekend in Milwaukee. Jim Hassettof Bakersfield State won the 200-yard freestyle (1 minute, 38.52 seconds), the500 freestyle (4:28.44) and swam on the 800 freestyle relay team that set aDivision II record of 6:36.67. Stephanie Keller of Cal Poly-San Luis Obispowon the 200 backstroke (2:07.50) and placed third in the 100 backstroke(1:00.5).;  BOWLING: Joe Perry, the former 49ers running back, averaged 190 inhis first appearance as a pro bowler and wound up 133rd in a field of 152 in asenior event in Colma. Paul Busch averaged 236.50 for six games to take thefirst-round lead.;  MISCELLANY: Benny Pierce, 57, athletic director andfootball coach at Saratoga High, was listed in stable condition at GoodSamaritan Hospital after undergoing double bypass surgery Monday. . . . Freesafety Ronnie Lott said he guarantees that he and the other 49ers will show upfor &quot;Dream Camp I,&quot; a fantasy football camp May 14-19 at Stanford. QuarterbackJoe Montana and wide receivers Jerry Rice and John Taylor are among the 49ersexpected to attend. &quot;We're all very close to (former Menlo Atherton Highcoach) Ben Parks and we're doing it out of respect for him,&quot; Lott said. &quot;Thenthere's (former Los Gatos High coach) Charlie Wedemeyer and all he's given tothe community. That's enough for anyone to be involved in it.&quot; Parks andWedemeyer were instrumental in organizing the camp.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910319  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  446  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday March 19, 199100079202,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>